Hi! Where can I report scammers? I got some hbar from accounts 0.0.1783695 and 0.0.1984664 with a memo that links to a fake Hedera website

The memo was "Your airdrop reward is waiting for you - rewardhbar.com" and the fake website looks EXACTLY like the real Hedera website. It has buttons to a fake MyHBARwallet website (which I didn't visit) so be aware for this (new?) type of scams!

@louweal Hedera isn't a centralized platform, only centralized platforms has the power to close accounts. You don't want your DLT to be centralized otherwise a bunch of famous people could report your account has being illegal and you wouldn't have any means to protect your funds from being confiscated.

The best defense has always been education. Scams will always be around regardless what technology you use. With decentralization, education is even more important. More people are educated, less people get scammed. This is true of ANY industry.

No single or group of parties should have control over your account. Unfortunately, you can't have a rule that protects account but also gives full power to ban scammers. Those are contradictions when it comes to the DLT space.
Lets hope that my post has warned/educated someone then. It's so frustrating that there are so many scammers around and that there is nothing we can do about it.
What you can do is maybe report the website directly to Hedera support through email. They will maybe try a DMCA takedown

There is something we can do about it, it's giving control to the powers at be, but that's the opposite that blockchains is trying to accomplish. Regardless which tech or path you choose, there are always tradeoffs

**Mainnet network proxies disabled**
Identified - Today, attackers exploited the Smart Contract Service code of the Hedera mainnet to transfer Hedera Token Service tokens held by victims’ accounts to their own account. The attacker targeted accounts used as liquidity pools at multiple DEXes that use Uniswap v2-derived contract code ported over to use the Hedera Token Service, including Pangolin, SaucerSwap, and HeliSwap. When the attackers moved tokens obtained through these attacks over the Hashport bridge, the bridge operators detected the activity and took swift action to disable it.

The Hedera community, including Swirlds Labs, The HBAR Foundation, Limechain, Pangolin, SaucerSwap, and HeliSwap teams, worked together to investigate the attack. To prevent the attacker from being able to steal more tokens, Hedera turned off mainnet proxies, which removed user access to the mainnet. The team has identified the root cause of the issue and are working on a solution.
Once the solution is ready, Hedera Council members will sign transactions to approve the deployment of the code on mainnet to remove this vulnerability, at which point the mainnet proxies will be turned back on, allowing normal activity to resume.

Creating a Testnet Account on Hedera Developer Portal

In other blockchain networks, we typically get testnet tokens via a faucet. However, in Hedera, instead of using a faucet, we create a testnet account on the Hedera Developer Portal. Every 24 hours, your testnet account will have its balance topped up to 10,000 testnet HBAR tokens. 

Follow the steps below to create a testnet account:

    Head to the Hedera Developer Portal (https://portal.hedera.com/register)
    Sign up for an account. You’ll need to verify the OTP with your email
    After you’ve set up your profile, you’ll be redirected to the home screen. Press on ‘CREATE ACCOUNT’, you should get an output similar to the image in ‘Expected output’


And as simple as that, we’ve created our testnet account on the Hedera Developer Portal!

Creating a Wallet Using HashPack

Now let’s create another wallet. This time, let’s use the HashPack wallet to do so. Follow the steps below to create a wallet using HashPack:

    Head to the download page of HashPack here
    As a browser extension, HashPack currently only supports Google Chrome. If you’re a Google Chrome user, then you can press on ‘Install on Chrome’ to have it installed. Otherwise, you can proceed with ‘Launch Web App’ for the browser version of HashPack
    Once HashPack is opened (either via the Chrome extension or the web app), press on ‘Create a new wallet’ and enter a password of your choice
    Tick the ‘Testnet account’ checkbox and press on ‘Advanced wallet creation’
    Make sure to store your seed phrase in a secure location. On the next screen, fill up the phrase verification check
    Lastly, give your wallet a name of your choice, select ‘US Dollar’ (should be the default option) and press on ‘Create Wallet’. You’ll be prompted again to ensure that you’ve saved your seed phrase in a secure location. Tick the checkbox and press on ‘Let’s go!’. If you face issues creating an account, refer to the troubleshooting help at the bottom of this step

And we’re done creating our second wallet! At this point, your screen should look similar to the image in ‘Expected output’. You should see 100 HBAR tokens in your wallet - these tokens are airdropped into our wallet at the point of wallet creation (only applicable for testnet accounts). You might need to press on the refresh button on the top right corner of your wallet to reflect the changes.

Make sure that there’s the pink border along the top of your wallet that states “You are currently using testnet”. If you don’t see the pink border, it is likely that you have accidentally created a mainnet wallet instead.
